"Abstract This paper examines the development of Internet taxation legislation, by the United States in particular, and by the OECD and the EC in general. In addition an examination is made of the scope and limitations of Tax 2 applications in Internet 3 Access 4 and in Electronic Commerce 5 . Although a moratorium on new Internet taxes has been granted through the enactment of the US Internet Tax Freedom Act; H.R. 4328 21 October 1998, this paper emphasizes that there are still existing taxes which will be applied in electronic commerce. Furthermore it is pointed out that there are strong pressures building amongst taxation revenue agencies to expand the tax base. These pressures will grow, it is contended, as the size of the electronic commerce market grows."
